<body>

<h1>@HI{{kara}}</h1>

<h2> Formation </h2>

<ol>
<li> @N{{}}@EM{{@HI{{kara}}}}.
<li> @Vte{{}}@EM{{@HI{{kara}}}}.
<li> @S{{}}@EM{{@HI{{kara}}}}, ...
</ol>

<h2> Definition </h2>

<p>
@EM{{@HI{{kara}}}} is a particle which can be used in a number of ways, generally with a meaning
of "from" or "after".
</p>

@BGRNDSTART{{}}

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
<a name="start">@EM{{@HI{{kara}}}}</a> can follow nouns to indicate the time at which something
starts or the place from which something begins.

<ol>
<li><table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{gold^going}}ha9@KJ{{time}}@EM{{kara}}@KJ{{open}}iteimasu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Banks open at 9 o'clock.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<li>
<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KT{{marasonn}}hakoko@EM{{kara}}@KJ{{exit^departure}}shimasu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      The marathon starts from here.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</ol>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
@EM{{@HI{{kara}}}} appears in certain idiomatic usages where figurative references to place are made.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{new^hear}}wosumi@EM{{kara}}sumimade@KJ{{read}}nda.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I read the news paper from cover to cover.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
@EM{{@HI{{kara}}}} can follow the <a href="grammar-te-kara.html">@HI{{te}}-form of a verb</a>
to mean that an action immediately follows the end of a previous action; the meaning here may be "after" or "since".

<ol>
<li>
<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{mountain^rice*field}}sanga@KJ{{large^study}}wo@KJ{{graduate^business}}shite@EM{{kara}}
      5@KJ{{year}}ninarimasu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Five years have passed since Yamada graduated from university.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<li>
<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{bright^day}}no@KJ{{evening}},@KJ{{eat^matter}}woshite@EM{{kara}}@KJ{{reflect^brush-stroke}}wo
      @KJ{{see}}masenka.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      How about a seeing a film after dinner tomorrow evening?
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</ol>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
@EM{{@HI{{kara}}}} can follow a noun to indicate the raw material from which something 
is <a href="grammar-tsukuru.html">made</a>. If the process is not complex and the original material can be clearly
discerned then @HI{{de}} is preferred.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KT{{wainn}}habudou@EM{{kara}}@KJ{{make}}rimasu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Wine is made from grapes.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
@EM{{@HI{{kara}}}} indicates the <a href="grammar-verb-use-of-passive.html">agent of a passive verb</a>.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{private}}ha@KJ{{large^use}}@EM{{kara}}@KT{{pa-texi-}}ni@KJ{{beckon^wait}}saremashita.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I was invited to a party by the ambassador.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
<a name="because">@EM{{@HI{{kara}}}}</a> can be used after a clause to mark it as a reason for something.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{busy}}shikatta@EM{{kara}}@KJ{{private}}tachiha@KJ{{public^park}}heikimasendeshita.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      We didn't go to the park yesterday because we were too busy.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
@EM{{@HI{{kara}}}} can be used trailingly at the end of a sentence to indicate censure of the listener.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{exertion^strong}}shinaito@KJ{{test^verification}}ni@KJ{{fit^status}}dekinai@EM{{kara}}.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      If you don't study you won't be able to pass the exam.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRNDEND{{}}

